@flexiarg peeragogy/stewardship-succession
@title Plan the Convener's Successor Before You Step Back
@keywords convener, succession, scaffolding, stewardship, hand-off, polycentric, drift, blackbox-recorder, peeragogy-handbook-stall
@audience peer-learning project conveners, founders, scaffolding leaders, organizers
@tone practical
@style process-pattern
@references [peeragogy/roles peeragogy/roadmap peeragogy/wrapper peeragogy/heartbeat collaboration-coherence/stasis collaboration-coherence/isolation]

! conclusion: Polycentric practices that depend on a convener for their kickoff energy need an explicit successor for the convener's stewardship role before the convener steps back.  Without succession, the practice continues at reduced scope but stops shipping its next canonical artifacts.  The convener's defining-reality / scaffolding-then-stepping-back move is incomplete without a third phase — naming who picks up the stewardship work, and what shape that work takes after the founder is no longer doing it.
  + context: A practice has a founder or convener who scaffolds the project's early years — defines the inquiry, recruits participants, holds the canonical-text production going.  Eventually the convener wants to step back: to make space for others, to reduce their own load, or because the practice should not depend on one person.  The community takes over the practice's *operations* (gatherings, conversations, ongoing work) but does not take over the *stewardship* — the quiet labor of pushing toward the next canonical milestone.  The result is a practice that continues but doesn't ship: the conversations keep happening, the milestones stop arriving.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: continued-presence ↔ released-control.
    Real: stepping back too soon leaves the practice without enough scaffolding; staying too long prevents others from picking up real responsibility.  The convener must release control AND ensure someone is positioned to carry the stewardship work, which requires explicit conversation, not just departure.
    Irreducible: stewardship is a specific kind of labor — neither the convener's founding energy nor any individual contributor's daily work.  It includes pushing toward next-canonical-things, holding institutional memory, and making decisions only a few people have the standing to make.  The labor doesn't transfer by osmosis.
    Active: the pull is strongest in the years after the convener's energy peaks but before they fully step back — a gradient phase when the next steward could be named but often isn't.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Named successor: the convener publicly names one or more people as inheriting the stewardship role, with explicit description of what that role is and isn't.
    (2) Distributed-stewardship council: the role is split across a small council, each member carrying one facet (canonical-artifact production, institutional memory, external relations, recruitment).
    (3) Time-boxed stewardship terms: stewardship rotates on a defined cadence (annual, biennial); each cycle's outgoing steward names the incoming one and writes down what the role learned.
    (4) Stewardship-by-shipping: the steward is whoever is currently shipping the next canonical artifact; if no one is shipping, that's the signal that no one is in the role.
    (5) Sunset clause: the practice declares an explicit decision-point ("if no one ships v4 by date X, the practice transitions to maintenance mode and stops claiming forward motion") so absence of stewardship is named, not silently endured.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: when someone asks "who is responsible for getting the next canonical thing out?", a name (or council, or rotation) is given that the named person(s) confirm.  Failing when: the question elicits silence or a generic "we collectively are."
  + ABSENCE-SIGNALS:
    - Canonical-artifact stall: the practice's canonical text/release/program-version stops shipping new editions while the practice's daily activities continue.
    - Rolled-up-sleeves drift: people are doing work but no one is holding the larger trajectory.
    - Founder-as-permanent-convener: the original convener never actually steps back because there's no successor in place; or the convener has stepped back informally but is still the only person with the standing to make some decisions.
    - Eulogy-language: the practice gets discussed in the past tense even though it's still active in operations.
    - Drafted-but-unshipped: proposals for next-canonical-things exist as drafts but nothing pushes them into shipped form.

  + provenance: This pattern surfaced from the 2026-04-29 posterior-pass analysis of the Peeragogy Podcast (M-peeragogy-rewrite mission), specifically the blackbox-recorder reading of episode 4 ("The Collaborative Process of Creating a Book", recorded late 2020).  In that episode, Joe Corneli stated: *"We're pretty keen to get a fourth edition of the peeragogy handbook.  I've even drafted a proposal for the fifth edition at one point."*  As of 2026, neither v4 nor v5 has shipped, despite the practice continuing in podcasts, Cool Laboratory, Future Trends Forum, Metacog reading group, and other forms.  Howard Rheingold in the same episode named the convener move as two-phased (define reality → step back) without a named third phase; this pattern names that third phase.
